<h1>
  When the Microbiome <span>Becomes Medicine</span>
</h1>

<p class="hero-sub">
  A microbiome story about recurrent infection, gut microbial balance,
  microbiome-based therapy, and the therapeutic power of microbial ecosystems.
</p>

<div class="story-image">
  <img
    src="/microbiome-therapy-cdiff.png"
    alt="Microbiome therapy illustration showing gut microbial restoration after recurrent infection"
  >

  <p class="credit">
    Illustration: PanorOmics original visual concept for microbiome-based therapy and gut microbial restoration.
  </p>

  <p class="image-explain">
    The image represents microbiome-based therapy, where restoring gut microbial balance can help protect the intestinal ecosystem after recurrent infection.
  </p>
</div>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The <span>Patient Story</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    A person with recurrent <em>Clostridioides difficile</em> infection may experience
    repeated cycles of illness, antibiotic treatment, temporary improvement, and relapse.
    Each recurrence can further disrupt the gut microbiome, weakening the microbial
    ecosystem that normally helps protect the intestine.
  </p>

  <p>
    Microbiome-based therapy changes the way this problem is understood. Instead of
    focusing only on eliminating one pathogen, it also focuses on restoring a healthier
    microbial community. The goal is to rebuild microbial balance so the gut ecosystem
    can better resist recurrence.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    Why the <span>Microbiome Matters</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    The gut microbiome is a complex ecosystem of bacteria, fungi, viruses, and other
    microorganisms. These communities help shape digestion, immune signaling, barrier
    function, metabolism, and resistance against pathogen overgrowth.
  </p>

  <p>
    When this ecosystem becomes severely disrupted, harmful organisms can gain an
    advantage. In recurrent <em>C. difficile</em> infection, restoring microbial diversity
    can become part of treatment and prevention strategy.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The Omics <span>Connection</span>
  </h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Microbiomics:</strong> profiles microbial communities and tracks diversity, composition, and recovery.</li>
    <li><strong>Metagenomics:</strong> reads microbial genetic material to identify organisms and functional capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Metabolomics:</strong> measures microbial and host metabolites that influence gut health.</li>
    <li><strong>Immunology:</strong> connects microbial balance with inflammation and host defense.</li>
    <li><strong>Clinical data:</strong> links microbial restoration with recurrence risk, symptoms, and treatment outcomes.</li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    What This Story <span>Teaches</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Microbiome therapy shows that medicine is not always about targeting a single
    molecule, gene, or pathogen. Sometimes treatment also means restoring an ecosystem.
    The gut microbiome can act as a living biological system that supports resilience,
    immune balance, and protection against recurrence.
  </p>

  <p>
    The larger lesson is simple: the microbiome is not just a passenger in human health.
    It can become part of diagnosis, prevention, therapy, and translational biotechnology.
  </p>

</section>

